Christian Pekeler wrote:

&gt;  &gt;&gt;      /**
&gt;  &gt;&gt;      * Runs the bare test sequence.
&gt;  &gt;&gt;      * This overwrites &lt;code&gt;runBare()&lt;/code&gt; in
&gt;  &gt;&gt; &lt;code&gt;TestCase&lt;/code&gt; such that exceptions in &lt;code&gt;tearDown()&lt;/code&gt;
&gt;  &gt;&gt;      * are only shown if the test itself didn&#39;t throw.
&gt;  &gt;&gt;      */
&gt;  &gt;&gt;      public void runBare() throws Throwable {
&gt;  &gt;&gt;          setUp();
&gt;  &gt;&gt;          try {
&gt;  &gt;&gt;              runTest();
&gt;  &gt;&gt;          } catch (Throwable e) {
&gt;  &gt;&gt;              try {
&gt;  &gt;&gt;                  tearDown();
&gt;  &gt;&gt;              } finally {
&gt;  &gt;&gt;                  throw e;
&gt;  &gt;&gt;              }
&gt;  &gt;&gt;          }
&gt;  &gt;&gt;          tearDown();
&gt;  &gt;&gt;      }
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Do you /really/ want to invoke tearDown() twice?
&gt; 
&gt; No. And it doesn&#39;t seem to. Do you have a failing testcase that shows
&gt; how this runBare() variation invokes tearDown() twice? 

Aha. Good point. The &quot;throw e&quot; in the finally {} block does the trick. 
It took me a little time to see that.
